Enfantillages Pittoresquesâ€ is the second of a set of algorithms that explore the basics of Generative Art, written with the aim of preparing artists for the script patterns of digital life. â€œEnfantillages Pittoresquesâ€ experiments with predefined plots, colour blending, webgl shaders, and generative music; all with a fresh, childish style. This algorithm has been trained to draw basic shapes in accordance to Satieâ€™s lyrics. However, it uses them in unusual ways and creates what looks like fantastic creatures, microscopic beings, or, to follow Corneille, Constant, and Appel: "human animals".

â€œIt took me four years to paint like Raphael, but a lifetime to paint like a childâ€ Attributed to Picasso (falsely, probably)

With two modes that wonâ€™t produce the same outputs, â€œEnfantinesâ€ are best experienced twice. In music mode, the code uses Satieâ€™s piano composition as a way of taming randomness, the sounds affecting the parameters of the strokes.

Hey, these have won me congratulations from the Shah of Persia and the King of Yvetot!

metadata.name: Evanescent Night #25
metadata.description:
In the placid silent nights, perhaps you could see the mountains stood out in silhouette, or they just melted into the mist, creating an illusion of dancing aurora.

The nights were so evanescent, that they swiftly faded from both your sight and memory.

However, sometimes you still recall the tranquility of the nights distinctly.

Press s to capture the moment.

metadata.name: Element #13
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Morixels Mega Colab #2 #22
Chaotic Grid Symphony #56
metadata.description:
This code is a mesmerizing visual feast for the eyes, creating an animation of a dynamic grid of black and white squares that appear to be constantly shuffling in a seemingly random pattern.
The grid is made up of an mesmerizing 128 by 128 squares, each one seamlessly transitioning to its new state as the animation progresses.

At the heart of the animation is the use of the noise function, which adds a touch of randomness to the movement of the squares.
This, coupled with the use of the "frameCount" variable, ensures that the animation is always evolving and never repeats itself.
The switch statement is used to cleverly determine the movement of each square, making the grid appear to be a living, breathing organism.

The icing on the cake is the interactive element of the animation, where the user can reset the grid at any time by simply clicking on the canvas.
And, to top it all off, the canvas is perfectly sized to fit the window, making it an immersive experience.
